Biden Admin Loses in Court to Texas on Immigration, Again


The Biden administration has lost another court battle to Texas over immigration, this time over its decision to end the Remain in Mexico program, or the Migrant Protection Protocols.

In April 2021, Texas Attorney General Ken Paxton and Missouri Attorney General Eric Schmitt sued the Biden administration after it terminated the Trump-era policy that requires foreign nationals entering the U.S. illegally to wait in Mexico until the completion of their immigration application process.

On August 13, U.S. District Judge Matthew J. Kacsmaryk of the Northern District of Texas granted Texas‚Äô and Missouri‚Äôs request for a permanent injunction, requiring the Administration to reimplement the MPP, ruling it had violated the Administrative Procedure Act.

The Biden administration had already lost to Texas in the first lawsuit Paxton filed against it, stopping an executive order attempting to halt deportations.

The administration next appealed to the Fifth Circuit and the U.S. Supreme Court, both of which denied its request to stay Kacsmaryk‚Äôs ruling, handing Texas two more wins.

The case continued forward in the Fifth Circuit, and oral arguments were heard before a different panel of judges on Nov. 2.

On Dec. 2, DHS announced that it had reached an agreement with the Mexican government, providing a range of guarantees in exchange for Mexico‚Äôs cooperation to implement the MPP.

But on Dec. 13, the three-judge Fifth Circuit Court panel didn‚Äôt accept the administration‚Äôs arguments and ruled against it for a final time, handing Texas yet another win.

Writing for all three judges in agreement, Judge Andrew Oldham ruled that the administration‚Äôs decision to end MPP violated section 1225 of the Immigration and Nationality Act.

Project Veritas' Epic Response to Rachel Maddow on Ashley Biden's Diary
By Nick Arama | Dec 18, 2021 9:45 AM ET

As we covered yesterday, the New York Times managed to confirm that Ashley Biden‚Äôs diary was real while doing all it could not to report on the troubling contents of the diary that pertained to Joe Biden. Instead, they tried to go after Project Veritas for their journalistic effort on the diary.

The Times calls Project Veritas a ‚Äúconservative group,‚Äù suggesting there‚Äôs a question as to whether they are even journalists. Indeed, they even cast Veritas as supportive of President Donald Trump to suggest this is some kind of illegitimate effort by Trump against Biden as opposed to journalism by Project Veritas.

Rachel Maddow went even further than that, suggesting that Project Veritas‚Äô effort to obtain comment from Joe Biden about the diary was ‚Äúextortion.‚Äù

‚ÄúIt does read, in the excerpts that you published‚Ä¶it does read like an extortion effort,‚Äù Maddow said to Michael Schmidt, one of the Times reporters on the story.

Here‚Äôs what the request from Project Veritas for comment to Joe Biden allegedly was.

But Project Veritas was still trying to use the diary as leverage. On Oct. 16, 2020, Project Veritas wrote to Mr. Biden and his campaign that it had obtained a diary Ms. Biden had ‚Äúabandoned‚Äù and wanted to question Mr. Biden on camera about its contents that referred specifically to him.

‚ÄúShould we not hear from you by Tuesday, October 20, 2020, we will have no choice but to act unilaterally and reserve the right to disclose that you refused our offer to provide answers to the questions raised by your daughter,‚Äù Project Veritas‚Äô chief legal officer, Jered T. Ede, wrote.

Rachel Maddow isn‚Äôt much of a journalist and doesn‚Äôt know what a request for comment from a real journalist looks like. So James O‚ÄôKeefe, Project Veritas‚Äô head, had to school her on it with the perfect response in the form of a Tik Tok video.
